                    <div class="CustomerReviewSummary">Better yet, don't think of the big money.</div>
                    <div>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Rating: </span>
                      <span>5</span>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Helpful: </span>
                      <span>1</span>
                      /
                      <span>2</span>
                      votes <span class="ItemCaption">Reviewed: </span>
                      <span>2005-05-19</span>
                    </div>
                    <span>I must say this book addresses a lot of issues for both the political and non-political audiences that most progressive books can't even come close to doing. Lakoff may at times refer to the way conservatives craft and frame their policies such as say tort reform so that what really happens is that trial lawyers end up giving to the Republicans and less of it to the Democrats just as they had easily manipulated corporate donors who only up to a decade ago gave more to the Democrats than to the Republicans. Those who keep insisting that it's all about the money are missing the point and that's one of the main problems this book addresses. Let's take another issue such as the so-called Mccain-Feingold campaign finance reform act. Here you'd have Senator McCain claiming that his bill would take the money out of politics and supposedly make it easier for more people to run for office. Add to it, Mccain like most conservatives would paint a few Democrats like Clinton and Torricelli or people associated with the party like Denise and Marc Rich as evildoers who will be punished once his bill goes into effect and in the process failing to mention that George W. Bush, Rupert Murdoch, and Tom Delay to name a few of the many conservative Republicans are the biggest culprits of dirty money campaigning. Sure, Mccain will falsly argue that Bush, Delay, Murdoch, etc ... are honest campaigners even when it's obvious that it isn't really so. Having read this book in addition to looking at the devil's details of Mccain-Feingold CFR it's obvious that Mccain and sadly Feingold had framed the bill so that soft money would be classified only on donors likely to be pro-Democratic while at the same time reclassifying the other soft money donors usually Republican as hard money donors and in the process allowing unlimited loopholes which is why Bush happily supported the bill in the end and was able to raise far more in 2004 than he raised in 2000 which of course was far more than what Clinton had raised in his 8 years in office. The problem of course is that once an argument is successfully framed, the rest of the work becomes easy, a concept Lakoff discusses as "slippery slope." Another interesting aspect that Lakoff discusses is how Democrats keep falling for the conservatives' frame trap and wind up in self-defeat. Revisiting CFR, last year, the rightwing media successfully painted 527s as Democratic while hiding the Republican donors from the screen despite the fact that Republican donors actually raised and spent 3-4 times as much money as all the Democratic groups combined and only to end up beating the Democrats 51 to 48. Money is not the answer to success; thinking and framing are. Conservatives don't want you to be independent thinkers and framers but instead want you to fall for their same deceptive frame traps which is how conservatives have been winning for the past 30-50 years. It's time to think and frame outside the money box. Buy this book, read it and learn to frame independently and progressively and together all of us can do what the politicans and the media can't and won't do: TRUE CAMPAIGN FINANCE REFORM.</span>
                  
                    <div class="CustomerReviewSummary">Who's afraid of the big bad conservatives ?</div>
                    <div>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Rating: </span>
