                    <span>If Howard Dean and others really think this is some kind of great revelation, then the Democratic Party is totally doomed.
<br />
<br />This is the same old line, "They vote Republican because they don't understand.  We are just not saying it right."  What "progressives" never seem to get is that people DO understand.  They also disagree.
<br />
<br />Do these people really believe that Conservatives have some "secret" knowledge about "framing" that the Democrats have been lacking?  And that Lakoff has just "discovered" it and now progressives can compete on a level field?  Ludicrous!
<br />
<br />Do you really think Rove knows tricks that Carville doesn't?  Do you really think Conservative strategists are really willing to stoop lower than Democrats?
<br />
<br />Why not offer people something they want instead of trying to find a way to turn their stupid, little, gullible minds around.</span>
                  
                    <div class="CustomerReviewSummary">Essential for Progressive Patriots</div>
                    <div>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Rating: </span>
                      <span>5</span>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Helpful: </span>
                      <span>32</span>
                      /
                      <span>33</span>
                      votes <span class="ItemCaption">Reviewed: </span>
                      <span>2005-05-12</span>
                    </div>
                    <span>As part of the Democratic Action Network here in North Carolina, this book was recommended to us.  Obviously, with John Edwards on the national ticket and not carrying the state, we are trying to focus on how to make change.  Progressives understand how Republican tax cuts favor the rich and pull the rug out from under working people, but in the face of "tax relief" speech find ourselves desperately needing a new language to describe "efficient government" that maximizes our "tax investment."  
<br />
<br />Progressives are continually startled when people do not vote for what is clearly in their own self-interest.  Lakoff addresses these issues in a focused and understandable manner.  Clearly, people who drive around with "W" on their gunracks have a perspective to which progressives must learn to speak.  Last week in western North Carolina, a preacher threw out 9 members of the congregation because they had the audacity to vote for John Kerry.  One Democratic congressional candidate was asked how she could be a Christian and a Democrat.  Clearly, we are involved in an ideological war, the dimensions of which progressives have greatly underestimated.
<br />
<br />I am particularly struck by Lakoff's view about how these two groups view God.  From his perspective, conservatives view a God who is wrathful and requires punishment, a very "old testament" view.  Progressive Christians view a beneficent God who loves His children.  But while conservative Christians are well organized, progressive Christians are only loosely aligned.  Much work needs to be done because people will vote against their own self-interest if they believe it to be God's will.  The Republican rich have manipulated these issues, ignoring that Jesus' gospel is that we should take care of the sick.
<br />
<br />Lakoff's argument on idea framing is helpful, but is new thinking for progressives used to thinking issue by issue.  I know I am going to need more than just this little book to really get the hang of this, but it is an interesting starting point.  For those of us puzzled by the direction of our country, befuddled by public unconcern of blatant lies and misrepresentations by the president with the war in Iraq, we need to reshape our thinking.  We need to redefine a "Clean Water Act" that encourages pollution as a "Dirty Rivers Act" or find conceptual ways to battle these ideas before Republicans succeed in polluting the planet.  Lakoff's book is a key to this; and is therefore essential reading for progressive patriots.     </span>
                  
                    <div class="CustomerReviewSummary">Lots of convincing to do besides truth telling</div>
                    <div>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Rating: </span>
                      <span>5</span>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Helpful: </span>
                      <span>27</span>
                      /
                      <span>28</span>
                      votes <span class="ItemCaption">Reviewed: </span>
                      <span>2005-05-12</span>
                    </div>
                    <span>I had always thought that it was only a matter of not being afraid to tell the truth and boldly take stands on doing what's right for the nation that would help the Democrats and progressives. Apparently, the last election convinced us otherwise. Sure, John Kerry was truthful and honest. However, it was not until the first presidential debate that he framed his ideas and then on the campaign trail it was nothing but back to repackaging Bush-lite. 
<br />
<br />Like Thomas Frank, Lakoff does agree that voters are ready to vote against their own economic interests but Lakoff takes it one step further. Conservatives and libertarians have one thing in common. They've figured out how to manipulate voters' minds into voting against their true interests. True, money can be a major factor but it's what libertarians and conservatives use to think ahead and keep the public brainwashed as long as they can.
<br />
<br />This book is non-partisan and proves that even if you're telling the truth, you need to get past the deceptive manipulative tricks conservatives and libertarians have used for the past 50 years by reframing the issues without backing down. That my friend is the key to success.</span>
                  
              
